Use ASP.NET Core's **`WebApplicationFactory<TEntryPoint>`** — it hosts your app in-memory and gives you an `HttpClient` that talks to it without opening a real port. Pair it with the official C# MCP SDK client.

```csharp
// 1. Add these packages to your test project:
//    Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Testing
//    ModelContextProtocol  (official C# MCP SDK)

// 2. Create a fixture
public class McpIntegrationTests : IClassFixture<WebApplicationFactory<Program>>
{
    private readonly WebApplicationFactory<Program> _factory;

    public McpIntegrationTests(WebApplicationFactory<Program> factory)
    {
        _factory = factory;
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task Initialize_ReturnsServerCapabilities()
    {
        // WebApplicationFactory gives you an in-memory HttpClient
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();

        // Use the MCP SDK's SseClientTransport (or StreamableHttpClientTransport
        // for the newer Streamable HTTP transport) pointed at your in-memory client
        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp/sse"),
                // Name is just for logging/diagnostics
                Name = "test-client"
            },
            httpClient   // <-- key: pass the in-memory HttpClient here
        );

        await using var client = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);

        // Now you're speaking full MCP protocol in-process
        var tools = await client.ListToolsAsync();
        Assert.NotEmpty(tools);
    }

    [Fact]
    public async Task CallTool_ReturnsExpectedResult()
    {
        var httpClient = _factory.CreateClient();

        var transport = new SseClientTransport(
            new SseClientTransportOptions
            {
                Endpoint = new Uri(httpClient.BaseAddress!, "/mcp/sse"),
                Name = "test-client"
            },
            httpClient
        );

        await using var client = await McpClientFactory.CreateAsync(transport);

        var result = await client.CallToolAsync("my-tool", new Dictionary<string, object?>
        {
            ["input"] = "test-value"
        });

        Assert.False(result.IsError);
        Assert.Contains("expected-output", result.Content.First().Text!);
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`WebApplicationFactory<Program>`** boots your entire middleware pipeline (auth, routing, MCP endpoints) in-memory — no ports, no external processes.
- Pass its `HttpClient` directly into the MCP SDK transport so all traffic stays in-process.
- If you use **Streamable HTTP** (newer spec), swap `SseClientTransport` → `StreamableHttpClientTransport` and point at your streamable endpoint.
- Override services for testing via `_factory.WithWebHostBuilder(b => b.ConfigureServices(...))` (e.g., mock databases, inject test auth).
- Make `Program` visible to the test project by adding `[assembly: InternalsVisibleTo("YourTestProject")]` or a `public partial class Program { }` in your server.
